  "prompt": "Is money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or organized crime) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to disguise the money's origin and make it seem as if it comes from a legal source.\n\nMost countries have strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering, and financial institutions are required to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nKey international efforts to combat money laundering include the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CTF) measures. Additionally, many countries have their own AML laws and regulatory bodies to enforce these rules.",
